  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Weak Business Plan</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The business plan is everything. Generic plans without specific financial projections or economic benefit arguments get rejected. Show exactly how Belgium benefits from your presence—taxes, potential job creation, or filling skills gaps. Get professional help if needed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Wrong Language</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Submit documents in the correct language for your region: Dutch for Flanders, French for Wallonia, either for Brussels. Don't assume English is accepted—it's not. Budget for professional translation of all documents.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Timeline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The full process (Professional Card + visa) takes 3-5 months. Don't book one-way flights or give notice on your apartment before approval. Plan financially for this waiting period.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Social Security Obligations</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Once approved, you must register with INASTI/RSVZ and pay social contributions (~20.5% of income). This isn't optional. Budget for these contributions from day one—they're in addition to income tax.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Late Commune Registration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register at your commune within 8 days of arrival. Missing this deadline creates administrative problems. Find accommodation before arrival and register immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Belgium -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Belgium</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Belgium has one of the world's best healthcare systems—high quality, accessible, and largely covered by social security once you're in the system. The transition from private insurance to the Belgian system is the main consideration for freelancers.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Structure</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Belgian System (After Enrollment)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ ~75% of costs reimbursed by mutuelle</li>
          <li>✓ GP visits: €25-35 (pay, then reimburse)</li>
          <li>✓ Specialists: €35-60 (partial reimbursement)</li>
          <li>✓ Medications: Heavily subsidized</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care: Mostly covered</li>
          <li>✓ Excellent quality nationwide</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Before System Enrollment</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>△ Private insurance required</li>
          <li>△ Full costs upfront</li>
          <li>△ Claim reimbursement from insurer</li>
          <li>△ 3-6 months before system access</li>
          <li>△ Emergency care always available</li>
          <li>△ Quality same, just payment differs</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How the Belgian System Works</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Belgium uses a reimbursement model. You pay for healthcare, then your mutuelle reimburses ~75% of the official tariff. Most Belgians also have hospitalization insurance for additional coverage.
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> Pay €25-35, reimburse ~€20</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> Pay €40-80, reimburse ~€25-40</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Pay 0-50% depending on category</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital:</strong> Reimburse most costs, small daily charge remains</li>
      <li><strong>Dental:</strong> Basic care reimbursed, cosmetic not covered</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Hospitalization insurance:</strong> Most Belgians have additional hospitalization insurance (€10-30/month) through their employer or mutuelle. As a freelancer, consider adding this for single-room hospital stays and reduced out-of-pocket costs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Belgium's Professional Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The effective minimum is €2,131.28/month—the Belgian "social integration income" threshold. Your business plan should show projected income above this level. Higher income strengthens your application.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak French or Dutch?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not legally required, but practically helpful. Brussels is multilingual (English widely spoken), but official documents must be in Dutch or French. For Flanders, Dutch helps; for Wallonia, French is essential for daily life.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work with Belgian clients?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes—unlike most digital nomad visas, Belgium's Professional Card allows you to work with anyone, including Belgian clients. You're a legitimate self-employed professional with full work rights for your registered activity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Five years of legal residence. Your initial Professional Card is 2 years, renewal is 5 years. After 5 total years with legal residence and integration (language, civic integration), you can apply for permanent residence or citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is Belgium so expensive?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          High taxes fund comprehensive social benefits—healthcare, pensions, unemployment protection, family allowances. You're paying into a system that provides extensive support. The trade-off is high cost for high security.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I choose Flanders, Wallonia, or Brussels?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Flanders has faster processing (60-90 days) and strong economy. Brussels offers international networking and multilingual environment. Wallonia is more affordable but slower processing and French-only. Choose based on your priorities and language abilities.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Belgium's Professional Card isn't a quick digital nomad visa—it's an established system for serious freelancers who want genuine EU integration. The application takes 3-5 months, the bureaucracy is complex, and the costs are high. But you gain something most DNV programs don't offer: a clear path to permanent residency and citizenship.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Brussels' location at the heart of the EU makes it ideal for consultants, policy professionals, and anyone working with European institutions or multinational clients. The multilingual environment, excellent transport links, and high quality of life justify the premium.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      If you're looking for a cheap, fast visa to work remotely for a year, Belgium isn't it. But if you're building a long-term European life with full social security benefits, Belgian PR/citizenship potential, and access to one of the world's best healthcare systems—Belgium rewards the investment.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
